# Final Review Proposal
**Producer:** agent:claude/claude-opus-4-6

## Summary

The implementation is comprehensive and well-structured. It correctly adds BackendExhausted as a terminal failure class, detects exhaustion via pattern matching in stderr/stdout, makes it non-retryable, and implements graceful panel degradation across all three panel types (final_review, completion, prompt_review) plus the engine's probe/preflight/resume paths. The OpenRouter adapter is also covered. Tests are thorough with good coverage of both degradation and all-exhausted failure cases. The quorum reduction math (.min(panel_size - exhausted).max(1)) is correct. The snapshot-journal reconciliation for stale Running snapshots is a solid defensive improvement. One inconsistency: prompt_review's exhaustion handler lacks the early-exit quorum check that completion and final_review have, which can waste invocations when quorum is already impossible.

## Amendments

1. In `src/contexts/workflow_composition/prompt_review.rs`, the BackendExhausted handler inside the validator loop (around line 210-231) is missing the early-exit quorum check that completion.rs (lines 192-205) and final_review.rs have. After incrementing `total_exhausted_count`, completion.rs and final_review.rs compute `effective_min` and check whether `executed_count + remaining < effective_min`, breaking early if quorum is impossible. prompt_review.rs just does `continue;` without this check. Add the same early-exit pattern:
```rust
let effective_min = min_reviewers
    .min(panel.validators.len().saturating_sub(total_exhausted_count))
    .max(1);
if executed_count + panel.validators.len().saturating_sub(i + 1) < effective_min {
    last_exhaustion_error = Some(error);
    break;
}
continue;
```
Without this, if quorum becomes impossible mid-loop, remaining non-exhausted validators are still invoked (wasting time and tokens) before the post-loop quorum check fails.
   Rationale: Consistency with completion and final_review panels, and avoiding unnecessary backend invocations when the outcome is already determined. The current code is functionally correct (it fails at the post-loop check), but wastes resources on validators that can't change the outcome.
